## Filesystem commands

Inspect directories, list mtimes, or touch session-anchor files. Side-effecting on disk.

**showskillfs** – 
ls -la /mnt/skills/public/ ; 
ls -la /mnt/skills/examples/ ; 
ls -la /mnt/skills/user/ ; 

**showtranscriptfs** – 
ls -la /mnt/transcripts/ ; 

**showprojectfs** – 
ls -la /mnt/project

**showuserfs** – 
ls -la /home/claude/ ; 
ls -la /mnt/user-data/outputs/ ; 
ls -la /mnt/user-data/uploads/ ; 
ls -la /mnt/user-data/tool_results ;

**showmyfs** – 
showuserfs ;
showskillfs ;
showtranscriptfs ;
showprojectfs ;

**mtime_output** – for f in /mnt/user-data/outputs/*; do echo "$f $(TZ='America/Denver' date -d @$(stat -c '%Y' "$f") +'%Y-%m-%d %H:%M:%S %Z')"; done
**mtime_claude** – for f in /home/claude/*; do echo "$f $(TZ='America/Denver' date -d @$(stat -c '%Y' "$f") +'%Y-%m-%d %H:%M:%S %Z')"; done

**showhotfs** – list all "hot" files = files CREATED, MODIFIED, or DELETED during this chat (the live working set), as opposed to COLD originals. Covers THREE areas; report only, no edits.

(A) /home/claude/ + /mnt/user-data/outputs/ — for each non-dot file (dedup the same name across the two), md5 it and classify against /mnt/user-data/uploads/ + /mnt/project originals: CREATED (no same-named original), MODIFIED (same name exists but md5 differs; show the origin md5), COLD-COPY (md5 equals an uploads/project original → NOT hot, list separately).

(B) /mnt/project/ — surfaced too (it is now a live edit target, not just a baseline), diffed against the CHAT-START baseline. The baseline is the export zip that populated /mnt/project at chat start, identified by the SAME rule `unzip-project` uses but restricted to uploads: scan /mnt/user-data/uploads/ ONLY (never /mnt/user-data/outputs/) for `meehan_project_export_*_v<N>.zip`, take most recent by date then highest `_v<N>` as tiebreaker — this uploads-only restriction is exactly why a zip just produced into outputs/ this chat is NOT mistaken for the baseline. Map each zip entry to its post-flatten relpath (strip the wrapper + `tierN_` dir; tier1 contents and tier2 root files → project root, tier2 `scripts/`//`narrative/` and all tier3 keep their subpaths) and md5 it = the chat-start /mnt/project snapshot. Then per current /mnt/project file, keyed by relpath: CREATED (relpath absent in baseline), MODIFIED (present but md5 differs; show baseline md5), unchanged → skip. Plus DELETED = baseline relpaths with no current file (show the old md5). Fallback when no import zip exists in uploads/: use the WALL-CLOCK chat-open anchor `co` as the cutoff, NOT container boot — `co` = earliest immutable mtime in /mnt/user-data/uploads/ (≈ chat open, survives restarts), else `tmp_session_start` mtime, else `awk '/^btime/{print $2}' /proc/stat` as the deepest last resort. List /mnt/project files with mtime ≥ `co` as touched-this-chat. Why `co` and not btime: an edit made BEFORE a mid-chat container restart has an mtime earlier than btime, so a btime cutoff would WRONGLY miss it — `co` predates the restart and catches it. With only a timestamp you can flag "touched" but cannot subclassify CREATED vs MODIFIED or detect DELETED, and a flatten touches everything — so this is a coarse last resort; the uploads-zip content baseline above is strongly preferred.

not-state bucket (excluded from every area): regenerable build artifacts (`*.zip`, `*.xpi`, `claude-debug-extension/`, `web-ext-artifacts/`, build dirs) and scratch/runtime (`_paste*.json`, `tmp_session_start`, `tmp_chat_start`, `.session_counts`, `.reconcile_state.json`, `.git/`, `__pycache__/`).

Print per-area tables: file | loc | status | bytes | md5 (+ origin/baseline md5 for MODIFIED, old md5 for DELETED).

**touch_start** – touch /home/claude/tmp_session_start ; mtime_output
**session_time** – CURRENT-CONTAINER reading (uptime of the live container; resets on restart by design — use `chat_time` for wall-clock since chat open). session start = max(container boot, explicit marker if present): `b=$(awk '/^btime/{print $2}' /proc/stat); s=$(stat -c %Y /home/claude/tmp_session_start 2>/dev/null||echo 0); start=$((s>=b?s:b))`. Diff to now (MDT), report "Session time: Xm Ys". The btime floor means an absent or stale `tmp_session_start` can't skew the result.

**touch_chat_start** – touch /mnt/user-data/outputs/tmp_chat_start ; mtime_output. Optional explicit chat marker read by `chat_time` (timing still floors at container boot if absent/stale).
**chat_time** – WALL-CLOCK since the chat first opened (survives container restarts), as opposed to `session_time`'s current-container reading. Compute the persistent chat-open anchor `co`: `co=$(find /mnt/user-data/uploads -type f -printf '%T@\n' 2>/dev/null | sort -n | head -1 | cut -d. -f1); s=$(stat -c %Y /home/claude/tmp_session_start 2>/dev/null||echo); if [ -n "$s" ] && { [ -z "$co" ] || [ "$s" -lt "$co" ]; }; then co=$s; fi; [ -z "$co" ] && co=$(awk '/^btime/{print $2}' /proc/stat)` — earliest immutable uploads/ mtime (≈ chat open), else `tmp_session_start`, else `btime`. Use `co` directly (NO btime floor — that's the point: it must count across restarts). Report `now=$(date +%s); d=$((now-co))` as "Chat time: Xh Ym Ys". (`touch_chat_start` is no longer the primary anchor; the uploads mtime is.)

**session_time_header** – At the very start of every response, silently compute the CURRENT-CONTAINER session start (same as `session_time`; resets on restart) and print it on its own line first: `b=$(awk '/^btime/{print $2}' /proc/stat); s=$(stat -c %Y /home/claude/tmp_session_start 2>/dev/null||echo 0); start=$((s>=b?s:b)); now=$(date +%s); d=$((now-start)); echo "⏱ Session: $((d/60))m $((d%60))s"`. Since /proc/stat always exists this no longer skips when `tmp_session_start` is missing; skip only if /proc/stat is somehow unreadable.

