## Worker functions

These are the workers invoked by pipeline families (see Conventions § Pipeline family pattern). Each can also be invoked directly.

**fix-silent** – find and fix all bugs silently, no per-fix commentary
**fix-broad-silent** – fix-silent plus style, naming, comments, dead code, anything improvable
**fix-security-silent** – security-focused review; thorough pass looking specifically at injection risks, privilege issues, information leakage, unsafe patterns. Fix all silently, no per-fix commentary.
**fix-perf-review-silent** – Review from the viewpoint of a performance expert. Anything that is unclear, inconsistent, or hard to use should be flagged as an issue. Then run sequential-fixes.
**fix-api-review-silent** – Review from the viewpoint of an API expert. Anything that is unclear, inconsistent, or hard to use should be flagged as an issue. Then run sequential-fixes.
**md-update-silent** – Update the existing .md with any implementation details that someone using these functions should understand, especially around error handling. Then run sequential-fixes.
**schema-update-silent** – Update the existing .schema with the full range of behavior that the .py has around sql activity. Then run sequential-fixes.
**fix-rewrite-silent** – fresh read of the whole file, rewrite any section that isn't clean, no per-fix-commentary.
**fix-rewrite-keepcomments-silent** – fresh read of the whole file, rewrite any section that isn't clean but keep all comments, no per-fix-commentary.

## turn counter and tool call counter
**session_counts*** - 
f=/home/claude/.session_counts
[ -f "$f" ] || echo "0 0" > "$f"
read turns tools < "$f"
turns=$((turns + 1))
echo "$turns $tools" > "$f"
echo "🔢 Turn $turns · tool calls so far: $tools"

**session_counts_header** — Trigger: at the start of every response, run session_counts and display its output on its own line first. Skip silently if /home/claude/.session_counts cannot be created or written.

**session_counts_resync** T C — Reset the session counter file to a known-good state. Run: f=/home/claude/.session_counts; echo "T C" > "$f"; cat "$f". T is the turn number that just completed (next header will display T+1); C is the cumulative tool-call total through end of that turn. Bypasses the normal increment-on-read flow. Use when drift accumulates or after a session restart. Both args required; no defaults — silently zeroing would mask the drift the command is meant to fix.

**trim_for_preferences** — read `command_2.notes` (uploads or working path); produce a condensed paste-ready version: strip all prose explanation, motivation, examples, and cross-session blocks; collapse section headers into bold inline labels; reduce each command to a single terse line; save as `command_2_preferences.notes` and publish to outputs.

