## specific to the claude_browser_extension.sh hud data. copy/paste from hud with this command
**hud_audit** — paste a _claudeDebug.audit() snapshot. Persist to /home/claude/hud_ledger.json: if missing, create it and say so; else append the paste as the next entry and bump next_entry; after every write cp → outputs/hud_ledger.json. That file is the authoritative history — load it, flatten all entries[].snapshot.data, dedup per-request rows by id, and assess the new paste vs all stored history (TTFT, total time, tok/s, output size, thinking-vs-answer share, stop reasons, error/limit signals). Also append an in-conversation numbered entry mirroring the file entry. Flag drift and outliers; correlations not proof. At session start, if the ledger is absent, rebuild from any uploaded hud_ledger.json first; else start fresh at entry 1.


## Session resume
Continuity across a fresh chat. `resume_seed` (write, at end of a session) records a self-describing snapshot; `resume` (read, first thing in the new chat) verifies that snapshot's files by md5 and prompts for any missing or stale. Both single-shot. NOTE: Project knowledge does NOT accept or auto-extract .zip archives — persist files by adding them INDIVIDUALLY to the Project's Files section (they then appear read-only at /mnt/project/<name> in later chats). A .zip is usable only when attached to a chat (it lands in /mnt/user-data/uploads/ and can be unzipped there). md5 here is change-detection, not security.

**resume_seed** — generate `resume_seed.md`; write to the one-true working path, publish to outputs. Derive every fact from the actual working files / outputs/ and this session's edits; never invent; omit a section that has nothing. The file has five sections, each a literal heading that `resume` parses:
- **RESUME** — one line: "resuming; treat as session start (run `touch_start` + the session counters); follow my command system; for any command not in my live prefs, use the attached `command_2_preferences.notes`."
- **MANIFEST** — a table, one row per state-bearing file: `working_name | store_as | role | required|optional | origin(project|upload|session) | modified(y/n) | bytes | lines | md5`. Add a second md5 (the current /mnt/project/<file> hash) labelled stale when origin=project AND modified=y. Exclude regenerable build artifacts (e.g. .zip/.xpi). `working_name` = its one-true working-path name; `store_as` = the name to save it under in the Project, renaming odd extensions (.notes, extensionless) to a supported text extension (.md/.txt/.json).
- **LEDGER** — only if `hud_ledger.json` is part of state: its entry count, unique per-request rows (deduped by id), the id list, and the next entry number.
- **STATE** — completed edits this session; OPEN items (pending decisions / unresolved); DONE one-offs needing no further action.
- **START** — instruct the reader: run `resume` first.

**resume** — reconstruct the prior session in a fresh chat; run before any other command. Steps:
1. `touch_start`; session counters (so the ⏱/🔢 headers work this chat).
2. Read the MANIFEST/LEDGER/STATE/START sections from the pasted seed text, or from an uploaded `resume_seed.md`.
3. For each MANIFEST row, locate the file in this order: /mnt/project/<store_as> (persistent Project copy); /mnt/user-data/uploads/ (including extracting any uploaded .zip there and looking inside); then existing working paths. NEVER look for a .zip in /mnt/project.
4. md5sum whatever is found, compare to the row's md5. Report per file: ✓ match / ⚠ mismatch (say "equals known-stale" when it equals the recorded stale md5) / ✗ absent.
5. If any required file is ✗ or ⚠, STOP and print a checklist (exact filename + why it is needed) and ask the user to upload them; do not proceed on a required gap unless the user says "proceed degraded." Never accept a copy whose md5 != the manifest.
6. Once required files are ✓, rebuild derived state (e.g. the hud_audit ledger from `hud_ledger.json`), confirm with the ✓/✗ table, then await the next command. NEVER cp any file to a working path during resume — the user sets up the one-true-file when they begin working on it; a blind cp could overwrite a fresher upload.


## Session resume, but around unzipping of files to /mnt/project
**zip-project** — build a downloadable, versioned project export (the OUTPUT side; `unzip-project` + `flatten.sh` are the INPUT side). Runs `scripts/make_export.sh` per `create_zip_by_tiers.md` §7: classifies every file via `export_rules.conf` using `scripts/check_export_rules.sh` (which flags UNMATCHED / AMBIGUOUS), stages tier1/2/3 atomically in a tmp tree, gates (no UNMATCHED; non-empty tier1; packed zip_version == N), refuses N ≤ last seen, writes a README with archiveHash + sessionNonce, and emits `meehan_project_export_<DATE>_v<N>.zip` to /mnt/user-data/outputs/. Preview with `make_export.sh --dry-run`, or validate classification with `check_export_rules.sh <roots>`, before the real build. Exits 0/1/2. (Reminder: producing the zip does not persist anything — the human downloads it and re-uploads via the UI; LOADING_AND_PERSISTENCE.md.)
**unzip-project** — (1) Scan /mnt/user-data/uploads/ for *_YYYY-MM-DD_v<N>.zip; select most recent by date, highest _v<N> as tiebreaker. (2) If /mnt/project/ is non-empty: warn and ask — wipe (delete all first) or overwrite (same paths only)? If overwrite: list all paths inside the zip; if any file's relative path differs only in top-level folder from an existing file in /mnt/project/ with the same basename → abort with conflict report. (3) Confirm: "Unzip <file> to /mnt/project/ [wipe first / overwrite]?" — await y/n. (4) On y: wipe if chosen (rm -rf /mnt/project/*), then unzip -o <path> -d /mnt/project/. (5) If the tiers landed under a single top-level wrapper dir (i.e. /mnt/project/<wrapper>/tier1_live_state/... rather than /mnt/project/tier1_live_state/...) — the usual case, since the export carries its own folder — note that `resume` expects files flat at /mnt/project/<store_as> then RUN `flatten.sh here --yes` to flatten the tiers into /mnt/project (the unified flattener; replaces the old flatten_v.sh + flatten_mnt_project.sh — tier-merges the export into /mnt/project/: tier1 contents + tier2 WHOLE-DIR (root .md specs to /mnt/project/ root, scripts/ and narrative/ as subdirs) + tier3 contents; overwrite-same-name, never delete; prompts before removing the emptied wrapper; ends with showmyfs). The flatten runs automatically as the final import step — unzip-project does the whole import. (6) showmyfs (printed by the flatten).
